= Callout Blocks

Callout blocks are used to highlight specific parts of content, often used with code blocks.

== Basic Callouts

This is regular text with a callout <1> at the end.

<1> This is the explanation for callout 1.

== Callouts with Code Blocks

[source]
----
function example() {
  return "Hello"; // <1>
}

const result = example(); // <2>
----
<1> This function returns a greeting
<2> Call the function and store the result

== Multiple Callouts

[source]
----
if (condition) { // <1>
  doSomething(); // <2>
} else { // <3>
  doSomethingElse(); // <4>
}
----
<1> Check the condition
<2> Execute if true
<3> Otherwise
<4> Execute alternative

== Callout Blocks

You can also use callout blocks to create standalone callouts:

[callout]
====
This is a callout block that can contain multiple paragraphs and other content.

It's useful for highlighting important information that doesn't fit inline.
====


